V{{other people}}\u000a{{Infobox philosopher\u000a| name             = William Alston\u000a| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1921|11|29}}\u000a| birth_place      = [[Shreveport, Louisiana]]\u000a| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2009|09|13|1921|11|29}}\u000a| death_place      = [[Jamesville, New York]]\u000a| death_cause      = \u000a| residence        = \u000a| nationality      = American\u000a| era              = \u000a| region           = [[Western Philosophy]]\u000a| religion         = [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]]\u000a| school_tradition = [[Analytic philosophy]]\u000a| main_interests   = \u000a| books            = \u000a| alma_mater       = [[University of Chicago]]\u000a| institutions     = \u000a| notable_ideas    = \u000a| influences       = \u000a| influenced       = \u000a| awards           = \u000a}}\u000a'''William Payne Alston''' (November 29, 1921 \u2013 September 13, 2009) was an American philosopher. He made influential contributions to the [[philosophy of language]], [[epistemology]], and [[Christian philosophy]]. He earned his Ph.D. from the [[University of Chicago]] and taught at the [[University of Michigan]], [[Rutgers University]], [[University of Illinois]], and [[Syracuse University]].\u000a\u000a==Early life and education==\u000aAlston was born to Eunice Schoolfield and William Alston on November 29, 1921, in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]]. He graduated from high school when he was 15 and went on to [[Centenary College of Louisiana]], graduating in 1942 with a [[Bachelor of Music]] in piano. During [[World War II]], he played clarinet and bass drum in a [[military band]] in California. During this time, he became interested in philosophy, sparked by [[W. Somerset Maugham]]'s book ''[[The Razor's Edge]]''. After this, he engrossed himself in works by well-known philosophers such as [[Jacques Maritain]], [[Mortimer J. Adler]], [[Francis Bacon]], [[Plato]], [[René Descartes]], and [[John Locke]].<ref name="Shook2005">{{cite book|last=Howard-Snyder|first=Daniel|chapter=Alston, William Payne (1921\u2013 )|editor-last=Shook|editor-first=John R.|title=Dictionary of Modern American Philosophers|url=http://faculty.wwu.edu/howardd/alston/alstonforthoemmes.pdf|volume=1|year=2005|publisher=Continuum|isbn=978-1-84371-037-0|pages=56\u201361|accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref> After being discharged, he entered a graduate program for philosophy at the [[University of Chicago]], even though he had never formally taken a class on the subject.<ref name="Syracuse" /><ref name="SU">{{cite news|title=Emeritus professor of philosophy William Payne Alston dies|url=http://www.syr.edu/news/articles/2009/alston-09-09.html|newspaper=[[Syracuse University]]|date=September 18, 2009|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref> While he was there, he learned more about philosophy from [[Richard McKeon]] and [[Charles Hartshorne]], and he received his [[PhD]] in 1951.<ref name="Shook2005" />\u000a\u000a==Career==\u000aFrom 1949 until 1971, Alston was a professor at the [[University of Michigan]], and he became professor of philosophy in 1961.<ref name="Marquette">{{cite web|title=The Aquinas Lecture in Philosophy i|url=http://www.marquette.edu/mupress/Alston.shtml|publisher=[[Marquette University Press]]|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref> He then taught at [[Rutgers University]] for five years, followed by the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] from 1976 to 1980 and then [[Syracuse University]] from 1980 to 1992.<ref name="Shook2005" />\u000a\u000aHis views on [[foundationalism]], [[internalism and externalism|internalism versus externalism]], [[illocutionary act|speech acts]], and the epistemic value of mystical experience, among many other topics, have been very influential. Like most contemporary American philosophers, Alston is counted among the [[analytic philosophy|analytic philosophers]].<ref name="OppyTrakakis2013">{{cite book|editor-last1=Oppy|editor-first1=Graham|editorlink1=Graham Oppy|editor-last2=Trakakis|editor-first2=Nick|editorlink2=Nick Trakakis|title=History of Western Philosophy of Religion|url=http://faculty.wwu.edu/howardd/Alston%20in%20Acumen.pdf|year=2009|publisher=Acumen Publishing, Limited|isbn=978-1-84465-679-0|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\u000a\u000aTogether with [[Alvin Plantinga]], [[Nicholas Wolterstorff]], and [[Robert Merrihew Adams|Robert Adams]], Alston helped to found the journal ''[[Faith and Philosophy]]''.<ref name="Plantinga2009">{{cite journal|last=Plantinga|first=Alvin|authorlink=Alvin Plantinga|title=In Memoriam: William J. Alston|url=http://www.andrewmbailey.com/ap/In_Memoriam_Alston.pdf|journal=[[Faith and Philosophy]]|volume=26|issue=4|year=2009|pages=359\u2013360|issn=0739-7046|doi=10.5840/faithphil200926434}}</ref> With Plantinga, Wolterstorff, and others, Alston was also responsible for the development of "[[Reformed epistemology]]" (a term that Alston, an [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]], never fully endorsed), one of the most important contributions to Christian thought in the twentieth century.<ref name="Meeker">{{cite journal|last=Meeker|first=Kevin|title=William Alston's Epistemology of Religious Experience: A 'Reformed' Reformed Epistemology?|journal=International Journal for Philosophy of Religion|date=April 1994|volume=35|issue=2|pages=89\u2013110|jstor=40036246|doi=10.1007/bf01318327}}</ref> Alston was president of the [[American Philosophical Association]] in 1979, the [[Society for Philosophy and Psychology]], and the [[Society of Christian Philosophers]], which he co-founded. He was widely recognized as one of the core figures in the late twentieth-century revival of the [[philosophy of religion]].<ref name="Centenary">{{cite news|title=William P. Alston|url=http://www.centenary.edu/philosophy/Alston%20obit|accessdate=December 10, 2013|newspaper=[[Centenary College of Louisiana]]}}</ref> He was elected a Fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1990.<ref name="AAAS">{{cite web|title=Book of Members, 1780-2010: Chapter A|url=http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterA.pdf|publisher=[[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]|page=11|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Death==\u000aAlston died in a nursing home in [[Jamesville, New York]], on September 13, 2009, at the age of 87.<ref name="Syracuse">{{cite news|url=http://obits.syracuse.com/obituaries/syracuse/obituary.aspx?pid=133187512|title=William Payne Alston Obituary|newspaper=[[The Post-Standard]]|date=September 20, 2009|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Bibliography==\u000a* ''Beyond "Justification": Dimensions Of Epistemic Evaluation'', [[Ithaca, NY]]: [[Cornell University Press]], 2005. ISBN 978-0-8014-7332-6\u000a* ''A Sensible Metaphysical Realism (The Aquinas Lecture, 2001)'', [[Milwaukee, WI]]: [[Marquette University Press]], 2001. ISBN 978-0-8746-2168-6\u000a* ''Illocutionary Acts and Sentence Meaning'', Ithaca, NY: Cornell University Press, 2000. ISBN 978-0-8014-3669-7\u000a* ''A Realist Conception of Truth'', Ithaca, NY: Cornell University Press, 1996. ISBN 978-0-8014-8410-0\u000a* ''Epistemic Justification: Essays in the Theory of Knowledge'', Ithaca, NY: Cornell University Press, 1996. ISBN 978-0-8014-9544-1\u000a* ''The Reliability of Sense Perception'', Ithaca, NY: Cornell University Press, 1993. ISBN 978-0-8014-8101-7\u000a* ''[[Perceiving God]]: The Epistemology of Religious Experience'', Ithaca, NY: Cornell University Press, 1991. ISBN 978-0-8014-8155-0\u000a* ''Divine Nature and Human Language: Essays in Philosophical Theology''. Ithaca, NY: Cornell University Press, 1989. ISBN 978-0-8014-9545-8\u000a* ''Philosophy of Language'', [[Englewood Cliffs]], [[Prentice Hall]], 1964\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a{{portal|Biography|Philosophy}}\u000a* [[American philosophy]]\u000a* [[List of American philosophers]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{Reflist|2}}\u000a\u000a==Further reading==\u000a{{refbegin}}\u000a*{{cite book|last1=Battaly|first1=Heather D.|last2=Lynch|first2=Michael Patrick|title=Perspectives on the Philosophy of William P. Alston|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kcoCHJ6jitkC|year=2005|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-7425-1424-9}}\u000a*{{cite journal|last=Feneuil|first=Anthony|title=Percevoir Dieu? Henri Bergson et William P. Alston|trans_title=Perceiving God? Henri Bergson and William P. Alston|language=French|journal=ThéoRèmes|issue=2|year=2012|issn=1664-0136|doi=10.4000/theoremes.310}}\u000a{{refend}}\u000a\u000a{{Analytic philosophy}}\u000a{{Epistemology}}\u000a{{Philosophy of religion}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Alston, William}}\u000a[[Category:1921 births]]\u000a[[Category:2009 deaths]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American Episcopalians]]\u000a[[Category:American metaphysics writers]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Analytic philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Christian philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Epistemologists]]\u000a[[Category:Epistemology of religion]]\u000a[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\u000a[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\u000a[[Category:People from DeWitt, New York]]\u000a[[Category:Writers from Shreveport, Louisiana]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of language]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of religion]]\u000a[[Category:Rutgers University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Syracuse University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\u000a[[Category:University of Michigan faculty]]\u000a[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign faculty]]
